We have used stable S isotope ratio (<sup>34</sup>S/<sup>32</sup>S) to identify sources of sulphur 
entering soil-plant systems. We are also using highly enriched stable isotopes  
<sup>13</sup>C, <sup>15</sup>N and <sup>34</sup>S to investigate sulphur fluxes and interactions 
between C, N and S. Our ultimate aim is to develop a sulphur cycling model that is fully integrated 
with the existing C and N models, which can be used to help fertiliser recommendations.

